<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-11-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-11-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="198" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Sir
                                    <persName type="to">Julian Pauncefote</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-11-30"><hi rend="italic">November 30,
                                    1891</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note of the 25th instant, asking that the port
                            authorities at Boston may be instructed to take charge of immigrants who
                            are not allowed to remain in this country until the ship bringing them
                            is ready for sea.</p>
                        <p>I take pleasure in informing you in reply that your request has been
                            submitted to the Secretary of the Treasury for his consideration.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>